> - **Topic:** Object Design: Reusing Pattern Solutions

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Reusing Pattern Solutions** in object design refers to the systematic application of **well-proven, named design solutions** (Design Patterns) — typically catalogued by the Gang of Four (Gamma, Helm, Johnson, Vlissides) — to recurring design problems. Rather than inventing new solutions, the designer selects an existing pattern whose **intent, structure, and consequences** match the problem's forces, then adapts it through parameterization.

In the KTU 2024 Scheme context, this topic appears under the **Object Design** phase of the Object-Oriented Design Process (following Booch/Rumbaugh methodology), where after establishing the high-level class structure, the designer refines classes by reusing **micro-architectures of reusable objects** that have been validated across many systems.

The three canonical reuse mechanisms in object-oriented design are:

| Mechanism | Description | KTU Keyword |
|------------|-------------|--------------|
| **Inheritance (White-box reuse)** | Subclass extends parent, inheriting implementation | "reuse through specialization" |
| **Delegation / Composition (Black-box reuse)** | Object holds reference to another and forwards requests | "reuse through composition" |
| **Parameterized / Generic reuse** | Class parameterized over a type (Java Generics) | "reuse through parameterization" |

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine you are an **architect** designing a house. Every time you need a staircase, instead of inventing one from scratch, you pull out a **catalog of proven staircase designs** — straight stairs, spiral stairs, L-shaped stairs. Each design is a **pattern**: it solves a recurring problem (how to connect two floors) under certain forces (available space, budget, aesthetics).

**Reusing Pattern Solutions** in Java is the same idea:

- A **Strategy Pattern** is like choosing *different sorting algorithms* — quick sort vs merge sort — without changing the client code.
- A **Template Method Pattern** is like a *recipe* — the steps are fixed (boil, sauté, garnish), but each chef fills in the details.
- An **Adapter Pattern** is like a *power plug converter* — making incompatible interfaces work together without modifying either.
- A **Decorator Pattern** is like *adding toppings to a pizza* — you wrap the base pizza with cheese, then olives, then mushrooms, dynamically.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight:** The module emphasizes that pattern reuse reduces design risk, leverages collective design experience, and produces code that is more maintainable, extensible, and decoupled. Always justify *why* a pattern fits — pattern overuse is an anti-pattern.

## 1.3 Standard Metrics & Vocabulary

The standard set of metrics used to evaluate a reused pattern solution includes:

- **Coupling** (low): degree of interdependence between modules
- **Cohesion** (high): degree to which elements belong together
- **Pattern Density**: number of patterns applied per class (ideal: 1–2)
- **Indirection Levels**: layers of abstraction introduced by a pattern
- **Open-Closed Compliance**: a class should be *open for extension, closed for modification*

> [!IMPORTANT]
> A pattern is **NOT** a finished design — it is a **template** that must be customized to the application's specific context (participants, collaborations, and consequences).

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Concept Breakdown

### 2.1.1 Why Reuse Pattern Solutions?

During object design, the developer faces recurring micro-problems. Reusing patterns provides:

1. **Proven Solutions** — Battle-tested by the community.
2. **Common Vocabulary** — A team can say "use a Strategy here" instead of writing paragraphs.
3. **Improved Communication** — Patterns form a shared design language.
4. **Higher Abstraction** — Encourages thinking at the *pattern level* rather than class level.
5. **Reduced Risk** — Avoids architectural pitfalls already known.

### 2.1.2 The Three Steps to Apply a Pattern

| Step | Action | KTU Expectation |
|------|--------|-----------------|
| 1. **Identify the Problem** | Detect recurring forces/constraints in the design | Map forces to pattern intent |
| 2. **Select the Pattern** | Match problem to a known pattern's intent | Justify the selection |
| 3. **Adapt & Apply** | Map pattern participants to concrete classes | Customize the skeleton |

## 2.2 Classification of Reusable Patterns (GoF Taxonomy)

The **Gang of Four (GoF)** categorized 23 patterns into three families:

### A. Creational Patterns (Object Creation Mechanisms)

| Pattern | Intent | KTU Exam Tip |
|---------|--------|---------------|
| **Factory Method** | Define an interface for creating an object, but let subclasses decide which class to instantiate | Often paired with Template Method |
| **Abstract Factory** | Provide an interface for creating families of related/dependent objects | Family vs Single object |
| **Builder** | Separate construction of a complex object from its representation | Step-by-step construction |
| **Prototype** | Specify kinds of objects using a prototypical instance, then create new objects by copying | `clone()` mechanism |
| **Singleton** | Ensure a class has only one instance and provide a global point of access | Static instance + private constructor |

### B. Structural Patterns (Class & Object Composition)

| Pattern | Intent | Reuse Mechanism |
|---------|--------|-----------------|
| **Adapter** | Convert the interface of a class into another interface clients expect | Wraps existing class via composition or inheritance |
| **Bridge** | Decouple an abstraction from its implementation so both can vary independently | Composition over inheritance |
| **Composite** | Compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies | Recursive composition |
| **Decorator** | Attach additional responsibilities to an object dynamically | Wrapper-based extension |
| **Facade** | Provide a unified interface to a set of interfaces in a subsystem | Simplified entry point |
| **Flyweight** | Use sharing to support large numbers of fine-grained objects efficiently | Intrinsic vs extrinsic state |
| **Proxy** | Provide a surrogate or placeholder for another object to control access | Remote, virtual, protection |

### C. Behavioral Patterns (Communication & Responsibility)

| Pattern | Intent | Reuse Mechanism |
|---------|--------|-----------------|
| **Chain of Responsibility** | Pass requests along a chain of handlers until one handles it | Decouples sender from receiver |
| **Command** | Encapsulate a request as an object, thereby parameterizing clients with different requests | Undo/redo, queuing |
| **Iterator** | Provide a way to access elements of an aggregate object sequentially without exposing its underlying representation | Sequential traversal |
| **Mediator** | Define an object that encapsulates how a set of objects interact | Hub-and-spoke communication |
| **Memento** | Capture and externalize an object's internal state without violating encapsulation, so it can be restored later | Snapshot/restore |
| **Observer** | Define a one-to-many dependency between objects so that when one changes state, all its dependents are notified | Publish-subscribe |
| **State** | Allow an object to alter its behavior when its internal state changes | State machine via delegation |
| **Strategy** | Define a family of algorithms, encapsulate each one, and make them interchangeable | Composition-based algorithmic variation |
| **Template Method** | Define the skeleton of an algorithm in a method, deferring some steps to subclasses | Inheritance-based variation |
| **Visitor** | Represent an operation to be performed on elements of an object structure without changing classes | Double dispatch |

## 2.3 Inheritance vs Delegation — The Core Reuse Decision

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU High-Yield Concept:** Whenever you choose a pattern, you must justify the reuse mechanism.

$$
\text{Reuse Mechanism Decision} = 
\begin{cases}
\text{Inheritance (Template Method, Factory Method)} & \text{if subclass IS-A supertype and reuses code} \\
\text{Delegation (Strategy, State, Decorator)} & \text{if object HAS-A helper and forwards requests}
\end{cases}
$$

### Inheritance-Based Reuse (White-box)

The subclass sees the parent's internals. Example — **Template Method**:

```java
abstract class DataMiner {
    // Template method (final - cannot be overridden)
    public final void mine(String path) {
        openFile(path);
        extractData();
        parseData();
        closeFile();
    }
    protected abstract void extractData();
    protected abstract void parseData();
    void openFile(String p) { System.out.println("Opening " + p); }
    void closeFile() { System.out.println("Closing file"); }
}
```

### Delegation-Based Reuse (Black-box)

The composing class holds a reference to a helper and calls its methods. Example — **Strategy**:

```java
interface SortStrategy { void sort(int[] arr); }
class QuickSort implements SortStrategy { public void sort(int[] a){ /* quicksort */ } }
class MergeSort  implements SortStrategy { public void sort(int[] a){ /* mergesort */ } }
class Sorter {
    private SortStrategy strategy;          // DELEGATION
    public void setStrategy(SortStrategy s){ this.strategy = s; }
    public void sort(int[] a){ strategy.sort(a); }
}
```

## 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Symbol / Formula | Boundary / Constraint | Notes |
|---------|------------------|------------------------|-------|
| Pattern Intent Match | $P_i \approx F_j$ where $P_i$ = pattern intent, $F_j$ = design force | Intent must align with at least one force | Select closest pattern |
| Coupling Metric | $C = \frac{\text{Inter-class references}}{\text{Total classes}}$ | Lower is better | Aim $C < 0.3$ |
| Pattern Density | $D = \frac{\text{Patterns applied}}{\text{Classes}}$ | Ideal $0.1 \le D \le 0.3$ | Avoid pattern overuse |
| Indirection Levels | $L$ = number of wrappers | Practical limit $L \le 3$ | More layers = harder debugging |
| Open/Closed Compliance | Modified modules $\le$ Extended modules | $\Delta M \le \Delta E$ | Design for extension |
| Single Responsibility | One reason to change per class | $\vert \text{responsibilities} \vert = 1$ | SRP of SOLID |
| Liskov Substitution | $S \le T$ in all contexts | Subtype must honor base contract | Enables safe inheritance |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Pitfall:** Students often confuse **Strategy vs State**, **Decorator vs Proxy**, and **Adapter vs Facade**. Memorize the *intent*, not just the structure.

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Banking Systems**: Use **Facade** to simplify subsystem APIs (AccountFacade, LoanFacade).
- **GUI Frameworks (Swing/JavaFX)**: Heavy use of **Observer**, **Composite**, **Decorator**, **Strategy** (LayoutManager).
- **JDBC API**: Uses **Bridge** (JDBC-ODBC bridge, abstract JDBC API vs concrete drivers).
- **Collections Framework**: Uses **Iterator**, **Decorator** (wrapping `ArrayList` with `Collections.synchronizedList`).
- **Java I/O Streams**: **Decorator Pattern** — `BufferedReader(Reader r)` wraps `FileReader`.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Worked Example 1 — Refactoring to Strategy Pattern

### Problem Statement
A class `InvoicePrinter` has a method `print(Invoice i, String format)` that uses an `if-else` chain to switch between `PDF`, `HTML`, and `TEXT` formats. As formats grow, the class violates **Open/Closed Principle**.

### Step-by-Step Refactoring

**Step 1 — Identify the varying concern.**
The algorithm *varies*; the client (InvoicePrinter) does not.

**Step 2 — Extract the algorithm into an interface.**

```java
interface PrintStrategy {
    void print(Invoice i);
}
```

**Step 3 — Implement concrete strategies.**

```java
class PdfStrategy  implements PrintStrategy { public void print(Invoice i){ /* PDF logic */ } }
class HtmlStrategy implements PrintStrategy { public void print(Invoice i){ /* HTML logic */ } }
class TextStrategy implements PrintStrategy { public void print(Invoice i){ /* TEXT logic */ } }
```

**Step 4 — The context class delegates to the strategy.**

```java
class InvoicePrinter {
    private PrintStrategy strategy;
    public InvoicePrinter(PrintStrategy s){ this.strategy = s; }
    public void print(Invoice i){ strategy.print(i); }   // DELEGATION
}
```

**Step 5 — Client assembles.**

```java
PrintStrategy pdf = new PdfStrategy();
InvoicePrinter p = new InvoicePrinter(pdf);
p.print(invoice);
```

### Analytical Justification

$$
\text{Before:} \quad \text{Coupling}(\text{Printer}) = 3 \text{ (PDF, HTML, TEXT)}
$$

$$
\text{After:} \quad \text{Coupling}(\text{Printer}) = 1 \text{ (PrintStrategy interface)}
$$

This satisfies:

$$
\Delta E = 3_{\text{new strategies added}} > \Delta M = 0_{\text{modified lines in Printer}}
$$

Therefore, the design becomes **Open for Extension, Closed for Modification**.

---

## 3.2 Worked Example 2 — Template Method for Reuse

### Problem
Different file parsers (CSV, JSON, XML) follow a common skeleton: `open → read header → parse rows → close`. The skeleton should not be duplicated.

### Step-by-Step Derivation

**Step 1 — Identify invariant vs variant steps.**

$$
\text{Template}(T) = \text{open} \oplus \text{parse} \oplus \text{close}
$$

where `open` and `close` are **invariant** and `parse` is **variant**.

**Step 2 — Abstract class with template method.**

```java
abstract class FileParser {
    public final void parse(String path) {     // TEMPLATE METHOD
        open(path);
        readHeader();
        parseBody();                           // abstract step
        close();
    }
    void open(String p)        { /* default impl */ }
    void close()               { /* default impl */ }
    void readHeader()          { /* default impl */ }
    abstract void parseBody();
}
```

**Step 3 — Subclasses fill the variant.**

```java
class CsvParser extends FileParser {
    public void parseBody() { /* split lines */ }
}
class JsonParser extends FileParser {
    public void parseBody() { /* JSON parsing */ }
}
```

### Analytical Matrix

| Property | Template Method | Strategy |
|----------|-----------------|----------|
| Reuse Mechanism | Inheritance | Delegation/Composition |
| Flexibility at Runtime | Low (compile-time binding) | High (setStrategy at runtime) |
| Number of Subclasses | One per variant | One strategy class per variant |
| Inversion of Control | Yes (Hollywood Principle) | Yes (DI-friendly) |
| KTU Tag | "reuse skeleton" | "reuse algorithm family" |

---

## 3.3 Worked Example 3 — Decorator for Dynamic Reuse

### Problem
`Coffee` interface has implementations `PlainCoffee`, `MilkCoffee`, `SugarCoffee`. We need any combination dynamically without class explosion.

### Step-by-Step Derivation

**Step 1 — Component interface.**

```java
interface Coffee {
    String getDescription();
    double getCost();
}
```

**Step 2 — Concrete component.**

```java
class PlainCoffee implements Coffee {
    public String getDescription(){ return "Plain"; }
    public double getCost(){ return 10.0; }
}
```

**Step 3 — Abstract decorator.**

```java
abstract class CoffeeDecorator implements Coffee {
    protected Coffee decoratedCoffee;       // DELEGATION target
    public CoffeeDecorator(Coffee c){ this.decoratedCoffee = c; }
    public String getDescription(){ return decoratedCoffee.getDescription(); }
    public double getCost(){ return decoratedCoffee.getCost(); }
}
```

**Step 4 — Concrete decorators.**

```java
class Milk extends CoffeeDecorator {
    public Milk(Coffee c){ super(c); }
    public String getDescription(){ return super.getDescription() + ", Milk"; }
    public double getCost(){ return super.getCost() + 2.0; }
}
class Sugar extends CoffeeDecorator {
    public Sugar(Coffee c){ super(c); }
    public String getDescription(){ return super.getDescription() + ", Sugar"; }
    public double getCost(){ return super.getCost() + 1.0; }
}
```

**Step 5 — Compose.**

```java
Coffee c = new Sugar(new Milk(new PlainCoffee()));
System.out.println(c.getDescription() + " => " + c.getCost());
// Output: Plain, Milk, Sugar => 13.0
```

### Class Explosion Avoidance

$$
N_{\text{variants}} = \prod_{i=1}^{k} (n_i + 1) \quad \text{without Decorator}
$$

$$
N_{\text{variants}} = 1 + \sum_{i=1}^{k} n_i \quad \text{with Decorator}
$$

where $n_i$ = options for ingredient $i$. With $k = 3$ ingredients and 2 options each:

- Without Decorator: $3^3 = 27$ classes.
- With Decorator: $1 + 6 = 7$ classes.

---

## 3.4 Worked Example 4 — Adapter for Reusing Incompatible Interfaces

### Problem
Legacy `OldLogger` has `writeLog(String msg)`, but the new system requires `Logger` interface with `log(String level, String msg)`.

### Solution via Object Adapter (Composition)

```java
// Target interface (new system expects this)
interface Logger {
    void log(String level, String msg);
}

// Adaptee (legacy code - cannot be modified)
class OldLogger {
    public void writeLog(String s) { System.out.println("[LOG] " + s); }
}

// Adapter
class LoggerAdapter implements Logger {
    private OldLogger old;
    public LoggerAdapter(OldLogger o){ this.old = o; }
    public void log(String level, String msg){
        old.writeLog(level.toUpperCase() + ": " + msg);   // DELEGATION + translation
    }
}
```

### Justification

The Adapter applies the **GoF pattern intent** — *"Convert the interface of a class into another interface clients expect"* — by reusing the existing `OldLogger` without modifying it, satisfying **Open/Closed Principle**.

---

## 3.5 Analytical Matrix: Choosing the Right Reuse Pattern

| Symptom in Design | Recommended Pattern | Reuse Mechanism | Justification |
|-------------------|---------------------|------------------|----------------|
| Conditional algorithm selection via if-else | **Strategy** | Delegation | Family of interchangeable algorithms |
| Common skeleton, varying steps | **Template Method** | Inheritance | Algorithm structure fixed, steps vary |
| Need to add responsibilities dynamically | **Decorator** | Delegation | Wrapper chain |
| Interface incompatibility with legacy code | **Adapter** | Delegation | Interface translation |
| Subclass explosion for combinations | **Decorator** | Delegation | Eliminate combinatorial class count |
| Tight coupling between subsystems | **Facade** | Delegation | Simplified interface |
| Stepwise construction of complex object | **Builder** | Delegation | Construction separated from representation |
| One global resource (e.g., config) | **Singleton** | Static delegation | Single shared instance |
| Notification of multiple dependents | **Observer** | Delegation | One-to-many dependency |
| State-dependent behavior | **State** | Delegation | Behavior changes with internal state |
| Subtype discrimination via type code | **Polymorphism / Factory Method** | Inheritance + Delegation | Replace type codes with classes |

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

