# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question A1 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam - Model Question]**
**Q:** Differentiate between **Inheritance-based reuse** and **Delegation-based reuse**. Give one Java example of each.

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | Inheritance (White-box) | Delegation (Black-box) |
|--------|--------------------------|--------------------------|
| Mechanism | Subclass extends parent | Class holds reference to helper |
| Coupling | Static, compile-time | Dynamic, runtime |
| Flexibility | Limited (locked at compile time) | High (settable at runtime) |
| Java Example | `class Dog extends Animal` | `Car has-an Engine` (composition) |
| Pattern Example | Template Method | Strategy |

**Java Example — Inheritance:**
```java
class Animal { void speak(){ System.out.println("..."); } }
class Dog extends Animal { void speak(){ System.out.println("Bark"); } }
```

**Java Example — Delegation:**
```java
class Engine { void start(){ /* ... */ } }
class Car {
    private Engine engine = new Engine();   // composition
    void start(){ engine.start(); }          // DELEGATION
}
```

*(3 marks: 1 mark for each differentiation row + 1 mark for correct Java snippet)*

---

### Question A2 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam - Model Question]**
**Q:** What is the **Decorator Pattern**? State one real-world scenario where it is preferred over inheritance.

**Model Answer:**

The **Decorator Pattern** dynamically attaches additional responsibilities to an object without modifying its class. It wraps the original object through composition, providing a flexible alternative to subclassing for extending functionality.

**Scenario:** Java I/O streams — `new BufferedReader(new FileReader("data.txt"))`. Each wrapper (BufferedReader, InputStreamReader) decorates the underlying stream to add buffering or character conversion, without creating a subclass for each combination.

**Why preferred over inheritance:**
- Avoids class explosion (combinatorial number of subclasses).
- Responsibilities can be added/removed at runtime.

*(3 marks: 1.5 marks for definition + intent, 1 mark for example, 0.5 mark for justification)*

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Module Internal Choice)

### Question A (14 Marks)

#### (a) Explain the Strategy Pattern with a suitable Java example. How does it support reuse through delegation? (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**Definition:** The **Strategy Pattern** defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one, and makes them interchangeable. Strategy lets the algorithm vary independently from the clients that use it.

**Java Example — Sorting Strategies:**

```java
// Strategy interface
interface SortStrategy {
    void sort(int[] arr);
}

// Concrete Strategy 1
class BubbleSort implements SortStrategy {
    public void sort(int[] a){
        for(int i=0;i<a.length-1;i++)
            for(int j=0;j<a.length-i-1;j++)
                if(a[j]>a[j+1]){ int t=a[j]; a[j]=a[j+1]; a[j+1]=t; }
    }
}

// Concrete Strategy 2
class QuickSort implements SortStrategy {
    public void sort(int[] a){ /* quicksort logic */ }
}

// Context - delegates to strategy
class Sorter {
    private SortStrategy strategy;
    public Sorter(SortStrategy s){ this.strategy = s; }
    public void setStrategy(SortStrategy s){ this.strategy = s; }
    public void performSort(int[] data){ strategy.sort(data); }
}

// Client
public class Client {
    public static void main(String[] args){
        int[] data = {5, 2, 8, 1};
        Sorter s = new Sorter(new QuickSort());
        s.performSort(data);
        // runtime switch
        s.setStrategy(new BubbleSort());
        s.performSort(data);
    }
}
```

**How it supports reuse through delegation:**

1. The `Sorter` class **does not implement** any sorting algorithm — it *holds a reference* to a `SortStrategy` object.
2. When `performSort()` is called, it **forwards (delegates)** the call to `strategy.sort()`.
3. New algorithms can be added **without modifying** `Sorter` — satisfying the **Open/Closed Principle**.
4. Reuse happens via **composition (HAS-A)** rather than inheritance (IS-A).

**UML Class Diagram (textual):**

```
Context (Sorter) ----> Strategy (interface) <|---- ConcreteStrategyA (BubbleSort)
                                       <|---- ConcreteStrategyB (QuickSort)
```

*(7 marks: 2 for definition, 3 for Java code, 2 for delegation justification)*

---

#### (b) With a neat Java code, illustrate how the Adapter Pattern reuses an existing class with an incompatible interface. (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**Problem:** A modern logging system expects `Logger` interface, but the legacy `LegacyLogger` class uses `writeLog(String msg)`. We cannot modify the legacy code.

**Target Interface (Adaptee's expected contract):**
```java
interface Logger {
    void log(String level, String message);
}
```

**Adaptee (legacy class - cannot modify):**
```java
class LegacyLogger {
    public void writeLog(String message) {
        System.out.println("[LEGACY] " + message);
    }
}
```

**Adapter (reuses LegacyLogger via composition):**
```java
class LoggerAdapter implements Logger {
    private LegacyLogger legacy;
    public LoggerAdapter(LegacyLogger l) {
        this.legacy = l;            // composition
    }
    @Override
    public void log(String level, String message) {
        // Translate new interface to old interface
        String formatted = level.toUpperCase() + "::" + message;
        legacy.writeLog(formatted);  // DELEGATION
    }
}
```

**Client Code:**
```java
public class Client {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Logger logger = new LoggerAdapter(new LegacyLogger());
        logger.log("INFO", "System started");
        logger.log("ERROR", "Disk full");
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
[LEGACY] INFO::System started
[LEGACY] ERROR::Disk full
```

**Reuse Mechanism Explanation:**

- The **Adapter** wraps the `LegacyLogger` via **composition** (HAS-A).
- It implements the **target** `Logger` interface expected by the client.
- It **translates** calls from `log(level, msg)` to `writeLog(level::msg)`.
- Reuse is achieved **without modifying** the legacy class.

**Structure:** This is the **Object Adapter** form (composition). The class adapter form (multiple inheritance) is not directly supported in Java since classes don't support multiple inheritance of classes — only interfaces.

*(7 marks: 1.5 for problem statement, 2 for Java code of Target+Adaptee, 2 for Adapter code, 1.5 for explanation of reuse via delegation)*

