### Question B (14 Marks) — ALTERNATIVE CHOICE

#### (a) Explain the Template Method Pattern with a Java example. How does it differ from the Strategy Pattern in terms of reuse? (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**Definition:** The **Template Method Pattern** defines the skeleton of an algorithm in a method (template method), deferring some steps to subclasses. It lets subclasses redefine certain steps of an algorithm without changing the algorithm's structure.

**Java Example — File Parser:**

```java
// Abstract class with template method
abstract class FileParser {
    // Template Method - final so subclasses cannot override structure
    public final void parse(String filePath) {
        openFile(filePath);
        readHeader();
        parseData();      // abstract step
        closeFile();
        System.out.println("Parsing complete: " + filePath);
    }

    void openFile(String path)  { System.out.println("Opening: " + path); }
    void readHeader()           { System.out.println("Reading header..."); }
    void closeFile()            { System.out.println("Closing file."); }

    abstract void parseData();  // variant step
}

// Concrete subclass 1
class CSVParser extends FileParser {
    public void parseData() {
        System.out.println("Parsing CSV rows...");
    }
}

// Concrete subclass 2
class JSONParser extends FileParser {
    public void parseData() {
        System.out.println("Parsing JSON tokens...");
    }
}

// Client
public class Client {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        FileParser csv = new CSVParser();
        csv.parse("data.csv");

        FileParser json = new JSONParser();
        json.parse("data.json");
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Opening: data.csv
Reading header...
Parsing CSV rows...
Closing file.
Parsing complete: data.csv
Opening: data.json
Reading header...
Parsing JSON tokens...
Closing file.
Parsing complete: data.json
```

**Difference from Strategy Pattern:**

| Aspect | Template Method | Strategy |
|--------|-----------------|----------|
| Reuse Mechanism | **Inheritance** (IS-A) | **Composition** (HAS-A) |
| Algorithm Skeleton | Fixed in base class | Defined in each strategy |
| Variation Binding | Compile-time (subclass choice) | Runtime (setStrategy) |
| Class Count | One per variant | One context + many strategies |
| Pattern Type | Behavioral | Behavioral |
| KTU Keyword | "Hollywood Principle" — don't call us, we'll call you | "Inversion of Control" via DI |

**Why Template Method reuses the skeleton:** The structure (`openFile → readHeader → parseData → closeFile`) is written **once** in the abstract class and reused across all subclasses via inheritance. Subclasses only fill in the variant step.

*(7 marks: 2 for definition, 3 for Java code, 2 for comparison table with Strategy)*

---

#### (b) With a suitable Java example, explain how the Decorator Pattern supports reuse by avoiding class explosion. (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**Problem:** A pizza ordering system offers a base pizza and four toppings (Cheese, Olives, Mushroom, Pepperoni). Without Decorator, each combination needs a separate class — $2^4 = 16$ classes.

**Solution using Decorator:**

```java
// Component
interface Pizza {
    String getDescription();
    double getCost();
}

// Concrete Component
class PlainPizza implements Pizza {
    public String getDescription(){ return "Plain Pizza"; }
    public double getCost(){ return 100.0; }
}

// Abstract Decorator
abstract class ToppingDecorator implements Pizza {
    protected Pizza pizza;
    public ToppingDecorator(Pizza p){ this.pizza = p; }
    public String getDescription(){ return pizza.getDescription(); }
    public double getCost(){ return pizza.getCost(); }
}

// Concrete Decorators
class Cheese extends ToppingDecorator {
    public Cheese(Pizza p){ super(p); }
    public String getDescription(){ return super.getDescription() + ", Cheese"; }
    public double getCost(){ return super.getCost() + 30.0; }
}

class Olives extends ToppingDecorator {
    public Olives(Pizza p){ super(p); }
    public String getDescription(){ return super.getDescription() + ", Olives"; }
    public double getCost(){ return super.getCost() + 25.0; }
}

class Mushroom extends ToppingDecorator {
    public Mushroom(Pizza p){ super(p); }
    public String getDescription(){ return super.getDescription() + ", Mushroom"; }
    public double getCost(){ return super.getCost() + 20.0; }
}

class Pepperoni extends ToppingDecorator {
    public Pepperoni(Pizza p){ super(p); }
    public String getDescription(){ return super.getDescription() + ", Pepperoni"; }
    public double getCost(){ return super.getCost() + 40.0; }
}

// Client
public class PizzaShop {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Pizza p = new Cheese(new Olives(new Mushroom(new PlainPizza())));
        System.out.println(p.getDescription() + " => Rs." + p.getCost());
        // Output: Plain Pizza, Mushroom, Olives, Cheese => Rs.175.0
    }
}
```

**Class Explosion Analysis:**

$$
N_{\text{without Decorator}} = 2^k = 2^4 = 16 \text{ classes}
$$

$$
N_{\text{with Decorator}} = 1 + k = 1 + 4 = 5 \text{ classes}
$$

**Reuse Mechanism:**
- Each topping **wraps** an existing Pizza via composition.
- Decorators **forward** the base behavior and add new behavior.
- Combinations are assembled at runtime via constructor chaining.

*(7 marks: 2 for problem, 3 for complete Java code, 2 for analysis of class explosion and reuse via delegation)*

