## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Analytical Walkthrough: From Contract to Implementation

The following logical derivation shows how an interface progresses from a **pure specification** to a **working Java program**. Each step is critical and frequently tested.

---

**STEP 1: Declaration of the Interface (The Contract)**

We define an interface named `Drawable` that specifies a `draw()` method. This is the *specification* phase — we declare **what** must be done, not **how**.

```java
// File: Drawable.java
public interface Drawable {
    // Implicitly: public static final
    int DEFAULT_PENS = 5;

    // Implicitly: public abstract
    void draw();

    // Default method (Java 8+) — backward compatibility
    default void describe() {
        System.out.println("I am a drawable object with " + DEFAULT_PENS + " pens.");
    }

    // Static method (Java 8+) — utility
    static String canvasInfo() {
        return "Standard A4 Canvas";
    }
}
```

> **Conversion Logic:** Note that `void draw();` has **no body** (note the semicolon, not curly braces). The compiler automatically treats this as `public abstract void draw();`. The `describe()` method has a body — it is a `default` method, so it inherits the `public` modifier (but **not** `abstract`).

---

**STEP 2: Creating Implementing Classes (The Workers)**

Two classes agree to honour the `Drawable` contract. They **must** provide an implementation for `draw()`.

```java
// File: Circle.java
public class Circle implements Drawable {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Circle of radius " + radius);
    }
}
```

```java
// File: Square.java
public class Square implements Drawable {
    private double side;

    public Square(double side) {
        this.side = side;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Square of side " + side);
    }
}
```

> **Conversion Logic:** The `@Override` annotation is a compile-time safety check — it confirms we are genuinely overriding a method from the interface. If we mistype the method name (e.g., `draws()`), the compiler throws an error. **Mark loss alert:** Many students forget the `public` modifier here; the compiler will reject the code because interface methods are implicitly `public` and you cannot reduce visibility.

---

**STEP 3: Polymorphic Usage (The Magic)**

The client code uses the **interface type**, not the concrete class type. This is **program-to-an-interface**, a core OOD principle.

```java
// File: DrawingApp.java
public class DrawingApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Reference type is Drawable, object type is Circle
        Drawable shape1 = new Circle(5.0);
        Drawable shape2 = new Square(4.0);

        shape1.draw();   // Output: Drawing a Circle of radius 5.0
        shape2.draw();   // Output: Drawing a Square of side 4.0

        // Calling the default method
        shape1.describe(); // Output: I am a drawable object with 5 pens.

        // Calling the static method — note: via interface name, NOT instance
        System.out.println(Drawable.canvasInfo());
    }
}
```

> **Conversion Logic:** The JVM determines at **runtime** (dynamic dispatch) which `draw()` method to invoke. The variable type (`Drawable`) only restricts what methods you can call; the actual object (`Circle` or `Square`) determines the behaviour. This is **runtime polymorphism** in action.

---

**STEP 4: Mathematical Representation of Multiple Inheritance via Interfaces**

Java classes can implement multiple interfaces — solving the "diamond problem" of single inheritance. The relationship can be expressed as:

$$
\text{Class } C \models I_1 \land I_2 \land \ldots \land I_n
$$

Where $\models$ means "conforms to" and $I_k$ are interfaces. For each $I_k$, class $C$ must provide a concrete implementation for every abstract method declared in $I_k$ (or in any interface that $I_k$ extends).

**Example:**

```java
public interface Resizable {
    void resize(double factor);
}

public interface Movable {
    void move(int x, int y);
}

// A single class implements BOTH interfaces
public class ResizableCircle extends Circle implements Resizable, Movable {
    public ResizableCircle(double r) { super(r); }

    @Override
    public void resize(double factor) {
        System.out.println("Circle resized by " + factor);
    }

    @Override
    public void move(int x, int y) {
        System.out.println("Circle moved to (" + x + ", " + y + ")");
    }
}
```

> **Conversion Logic:** `ResizableCircle` inherits the `draw()` obligation from `Circle` (which implements `Drawable`), and additionally implements `resize()` and `move()`. The total contract is the **union** of all abstract method signatures across the inheritance chain.

### 3.2 Analytical Matrix: Interface vs Abstract Class

> [!NOTE]
> This is the **#1 comparison question** in KTU exams. Memorise this table.

| Feature | Interface (Pre-Java 8) | Abstract Class | Interface (Java 8+) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Method types | Abstract only | Abstract + Concrete | Abstract + default + static + private |
| Fields | `public static final` only | Any type | `public static final` only |
| Inheritance | Multiple (`implements`) | Single (`extends`) | Multiple (`implements`) |
| Constructor | None | Yes | None |
| Access modifiers | Public only | Any | Public for default/static; private for helper |
| When to use | Define a *capability* / role | Define a *base class* with shared state | Define an evolving API contract |

### 3.3 The "Specification" Angle — Why "Specifying Interfaces"?

The module title **"Specifying Interfaces"** emphasises the *design* perspective. In Object-Oriented Design (specifically using the **GRASP** and **GoF** patterns), specifying an interface means:

1. **Identifying the roles** objects play in a system (e.g., `Payable`, `Loggable`, `Serializable`).
2. **Documenting the contract** — inputs, outputs, preconditions, postconditions.
3. **Decoupling clients from implementations** — clients depend on the interface, not the concrete class.
4. **Enabling substitutability** — any implementation of the interface can be swapped in without changing client code (Liskov Substitution Principle).

