### **Question A (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`

**(a)** Explain the concept of an interface in Java with a suitable example. Discuss how interfaces support multiple inheritance in Java. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program to define an interface `BankAccount` with methods `deposit(double amt)`, `withdraw(double amt)`, and `displayBalance()`. Implement this interface in two classes: `SavingsAccount` and `CurrentAccount`. Demonstrate polymorphism using a common reference. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Question A

**(a) Concept of Interface & Multiple Inheritance (7 Marks):**

An **interface** in Java is a blueprint of a class that contains only abstract methods (pre-Java 8) and constants. It is used to achieve **full abstraction** and **multiple inheritance**, which is not possible with class inheritance in Java.

**Syntax:**

```java
interface InterfaceName {
    // abstract methods and constants
}
```

**Multiple Inheritance Example:**

```java
interface Printable {
    void print();
}

interface Scannable {
    void scan();
}

// Class implements BOTH interfaces — multiple inheritance
class MultifunctionPrinter implements Printable, Scannable {
    public void print() {
        System.out.println("Printing document...");
    }
    public void scan() {
        System.out.println("Scanning document...");
    }
}
```

**Key Advantages:**
- A class can implement any number of interfaces.
- Interfaces enable **loose coupling** and **polymorphism**.
- They support the **"program to an interface, not an implementation"** OOD principle.

---

**(b) Complete Java Program — BankAccount Interface (7 Marks):**

```java
// Step 1: Define the interface
interface BankAccount {
    void deposit(double amt);
    void withdraw(double amt);
    void displayBalance();
}

// Step 2: SavingsAccount implements BankAccount
class SavingsAccount implements BankAccount {
    private double balance = 0.0;
    private static final double INTEREST_RATE = 0.04;

    public void deposit(double amt) {
        balance += amt;
        System.out.println("Deposited " + amt + " into Savings.");
    }

    public void withdraw(double amt) {
        if (balance >= amt) {
            balance -= amt;
            System.out.println("Withdrew " + amt + " from Savings.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Insufficient balance in Savings.");
        }
    }

    public void displayBalance() {
        System.out.println("Savings Balance: " + balance);
    }
}

// Step 3: CurrentAccount implements BankAccount
class CurrentAccount implements BankAccount {
    private double balance = 0.0;

    public void deposit(double amt) {
        balance += amt;
        System.out.println("Deposited " + amt + " into Current.");
    }

    public void withdraw(double amt) {
        balance -= amt; // Overdraft allowed
        System.out.println("Withdrew " + amt + " from Current.");
    }

    public void displayBalance() {
        System.out.println("Current Balance: " + balance);
    }
}

// Step 4: Client Code Demonstrating Polymorphism
public class BankDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount account1 = new SavingsAccount(); // Polymorphic reference
        BankAccount account2 = new CurrentAccount(); // Polymorphic reference

        account1.deposit(10000);
        account1.withdraw(2000);
        account1.displayBalance();

        account2.deposit(20000);
        account2.withdraw(25000);
        account2.displayBalance();
    }
}
```

**Sample Output:**

```
Deposited 10000.0 into Savings.
Withdrew 2000.0 from Savings.
Savings Balance: 8000.0
Deposited 20000.0 into Current.
Withdrew 25000.0 from Current.
Current Balance: -5000.0
```

**Explanation of Polymorphism (for marks):**
The reference type `BankAccount` is used in the client code. At runtime, the JVM determines whether to invoke `SavingsAccount` or `CurrentAccount` methods. This decoupling means new account types (e.g., `FixedDepositAccount`) can be added without modifying `BankDemo`.

