### **Question B (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam – May 2024]`

**(a)** Explain the evolution of interfaces in Java from Java 7 to Java 9. Discuss `default`, `static`, and `private` methods in interfaces with examples. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Design an interface `Payable` with a method `getPayment(double hoursWorked, double ratePerHour)`. Implement it in classes `ContractEmployee` and `PermanentEmployee` where the former receives the basic pay and the latter receives the basic pay plus a 20% bonus. Write a driver class to test the implementation. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Question B

**(a) Evolution of Interfaces in Java (7 Marks):**

| Java Version | Feature Added | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Java 7 and earlier** | Only abstract methods + `public static final` fields | Pure contract specification |
| **Java 8** | `default` methods | Allow concrete implementation; backward-compatible API evolution |
| **Java 8** | `static` methods | Group utility methods inside the interface |
| **Java 9** | `private` methods | Internal helper methods for `default` methods; code reuse without exposing internals |

**Example Demonstrating All Features:**

```java
interface PaymentGateway {
    // 1. Constant (implicitly public static final)
    double TRANSACTION_FEE = 2.5;

    // 2. Abstract method
    void processPayment(double amount);

    // 3. Default method (Java 8)
    default void printReceipt(double amount) {
        double netAmount = amount + TRANSACTION_FEE;
        log("Receipt generated for amount: " + netAmount);
        System.out.println("Receipt: Net amount = " + netAmount);
    }

    // 4. Static method (Java 8)
    static boolean isValidAmount(double amount) {
        return amount > 0;
    }

    // 5. Private method (Java 9) — helper for default method
    private void log(String message) {
        System.out.println("[LOG] " + message);
    }
}
```

**Why This Evolution Matters:**
Before Java 8, adding a new method to an interface would **break all existing implementations**. The `default` keyword solved this by allowing the interface to provide a fallback implementation that implementing classes can optionally override.

