**(b) Payable Interface Design (7 Marks):**

```java
// Step 1: Interface definition
interface Payable {
    double getPayment(double hoursWorked, double ratePerHour);
}

// Step 2: ContractEmployee — basic pay only
class ContractEmployee implements Payable {
    private String name;

    public ContractEmployee(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    public double getPayment(double hoursWorked, double ratePerHour) {
        return hoursWorked * ratePerHour; // Basic pay, no bonus
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}

// Step 3: PermanentEmployee — basic pay + 20% bonus
class PermanentEmployee implements Payable {
    private String name;
    private static final double BONUS_PERCENT = 0.20;

    public PermanentEmployee(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    public double getPayment(double hoursWorked, double ratePerHour) {
        double basic = hoursWorked * ratePerHour;
        return basic + (basic * BONUS_PERCENT); // Basic + 20% bonus
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}

// Step 4: Driver class demonstrating polymorphism
public class PayrollSystem {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Payable emp1 = new ContractEmployee("Rahul");
        Payable emp2 = new PermanentEmployee("Ananya");

        double hours = 160;
        double rate = 500;

        System.out.println(emp1.getName() + " Payment: Rs. "
            + emp1.getPayment(hours, rate));

        System.out.println(emp2.getName() + " Payment: Rs. "
            + emp2.getPayment(hours, rate));
    }
}
```

**Sample Output:**

```
Rahul Payment: Rs. 80000.0
Ananya Payment: Rs. 96000.0
```

**Explanation (for marks):**
The `Payable` interface establishes a uniform contract for all employee types. The driver class `PayrollSystem` uses the interface reference type, demonstrating that any class implementing `Payable` can be substituted — a practical application of the **Liskov Substitution Principle**.

