### 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mark-Loss Pitfalls in Interface Questions:**
>
> 1. **Forgetting `public` modifier on overridden methods** (–2 marks): Interface methods are implicitly `public`. Writing `void draw() {}` (package-private) will cause a compile error. Always write `@Override public void draw() { ... }`.
>
> 2. **Confusing `default` methods with `abstract` methods** (–1 mark): A `default` method **has a body** and provides a fallback. An abstract method has **no body** and **must** be implemented. Do not put `default` and `abstract` on the same method.
>
> 3. **Trying to instantiate an interface** (–2 marks): Writing `Drawable d = new Drawable();` is illegal. You must instantiate a concrete implementing class.
>
> 4. **Forgetting `@Override` annotation** (–0.5 mark): Although not a compile error, KTU evaluators deduct marks for not demonstrating the use of `@Override` in interface implementation.
>
> 5. **Marking interface fields as instance variables** (–1 mark): All interface fields are **constants** (`public static final`). You cannot have mutable state in an interface.
>
> 6. **Calling a `static` interface method via an instance reference** (–1 mark): Always use `InterfaceName.staticMethod()`, not `instance.staticMethod()`.

