### 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Specifying Interfaces:**

- An **interface** is a contract specifying method signatures that implementing classes **must** honour.
- Pre-Java 8 interfaces support only **abstract methods** and **constants**.
- Java 8 introduced **`default`** (concrete instance methods) and **`static`** (utility) methods in interfaces.
- Java 9 added **`private`** methods to interfaces for internal code reuse.
- All interface methods are implicitly **`public abstract`** (unless `default`, `static`, or `private`).
- All interface fields are implicitly **`public static final`** (constants only).
- Interfaces **cannot be instantiated** directly; they must be implemented.
- Use the **`implements`** keyword for classes to honour an interface contract.
- Use the **`extends`** keyword between interfaces (an interface can extend multiple interfaces).
- A class can implement **multiple** interfaces — Java's solution to multiple inheritance.
- **Polymorphism** allows reference types of an interface to hold objects of any implementing class.
- The **"program to an interface"** principle promotes **loose coupling** and **maintainability**.
- **Functional interfaces** (single abstract method) are the foundation of **lambda expressions** in Java 8.
- Interface members cannot use access modifiers other than `public` (or `private` for Java 9 helpers).
- The `@Override` annotation is **strongly recommended** when implementing interface methods for compile-time safety.

