# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Breakdown — The Anatomy of an Interface

The interface specification mechanism in Java operates on **six core pillars**. Each pillar is described below with its semantic role.

1. **Implicit Modifiers**
   - All methods declared without a body are implicitly `public abstract`.
   - All fields are implicitly `public static final` (compile-time constants).
   - All nested types are implicitly `public static`.

2. **Method Categories (Java 8+ / Java 9+)**
   - **Abstract methods:** No body; must be implemented by concrete classes.
   - **Default methods (`default`):** Have a body; provide a default implementation. Allow **backward-compatible evolution** of interfaces.
   - **Static methods (`static`):** Utility methods associated with the interface; not inherited by implementers.
   - **Private methods (Java 9+):** Helper methods inside interfaces (not accessible to implementers).

3. **Implementation Contract (`implements`)**
   - A class uses `implements InterfaceA, InterfaceB` to honour one or more specifications.
   - The class must provide a concrete body for every abstract method (or declare itself `abstract`).

4. **Interface Inheritance (`extends`)**
   - Interfaces can extend **one or more** other interfaces.
   - This is Java's only legal form of **multiple inheritance**.

5. **Functional Interfaces (`@FunctionalInterface`)**
   - Exactly **one** abstract method.
   - Eligible for **lambda expressions** and method references.

6. **Marker Interfaces**
   - Contain **no** members (e.g., `Serializable`, `Cloneable`, `Remote`).
   - Used to tag classes with a capability or metadata.

## 2.2 The "Diamond Problem" Resolution

> [!IMPORTANT]
> When a class implements two interfaces that both provide a `default` method with the same signature, Java **forces the implementer to override** that method to resolve the ambiguity — otherwise, a **compile-time error** is produced.

```java
interface A { default void show() { System.out.println("A"); } }
interface B { default void show() { System.out.println("B"); } }
class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void show() {           // MUST override to resolve diamond
        A.super.show();            // explicit disambiguation
    }
}
```

## 2.3 KTU Formula / Rule Cheat Sheet

| # | Rule / Formula | Description | Exam Priority |
|---|---|---|---|
| R1 | `implements I1, I2, ...` | Class may implement **any number** of interfaces | **High** |
| R2 | `interface I3 extends I1, I2` | Interface may extend **multiple** interfaces | **High** |
| R3 | Methods in interface → `public abstract` | Implicit if no body | **High** |
| R4 | Fields in interface → `public static final` | Implicit and cannot be reduced | **Medium** |
| R5 | `default` methods need body | Added in Java 8 for backward compatibility | **High** |
