# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Derivation of Interface Compliance — The Type-Theoretic View

Java's type system enforces that an implementing class `C` **is-a** (subtype of) every interface it implements. Formally:

$$\forall \text{ class } C, \; \forall \text{ interface } I: \; C \text{ implements } I \implies C \leq I$$

where $\leq$ denotes the **subtype relation**. The implications are:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Given:} \quad & C \text{ implements } I, \; I \text{ declares } m(): \text{void} \\
\text{Required:} \quad & C \text{ must provide } m() \text{ with matching signature} \\
\text{Or:} \quad & C \text{ must be declared } \texttt{abstract}
\end{aligned}
$$

### Analytical Matrix — Interface Specification Decision Table

| Scenario | Rule | Resulting Construct |
|---|---|---|
| Single contract, multiple unrelated implementers | Define `interface` | `interface Payment { void pay(); }` |
| Share common code among implementers | Use `default` methods | `default void log() { ... }` |
| Tag a class with a capability | Use marker interface | `implements Cloneable` |
| Single abstract method → use lambdas | Use `@FunctionalInterface` | `@FunctionalInterface Runnable2` |
| Resolve diamond conflict | Override and call `I.super.m()` | `A.super.show();` |
| Reuse constants globally | Declare in interface | `int MAX = 100;` (implicit `public static final`) |

## 3.2 Worked Exhaustive Example — Complete Interface Specification

```java
// Step 1: Declare the specification (the "contract")
@FunctionalInterface
public interface PaymentGateway {
    // abstract method — the core contract
    void pay(double amount);

    // default method — optional behaviour with sensible default
    default boolean validate(double amount) {
        return amount > 0 && amount <= 1_000_000;
    }

    // static method — utility scoped to the interface
    static String currency() { return "INR"; }

    // constant — implicit public static final
    String CURRENCY = "INR";
}
```

```java
// Step 2: Provide a concrete implementation
public class CardPayment implements PaymentGateway {
    @Override
    public void pay(double amount) {
        if (!validate(amount)) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid amount");
        }
        System.out.println("Paid ₹" + amount + " via Card");
    }
}
```

```java
// Step 3: Client depends on the abstraction (interface)
public class CheckoutService {
    private final PaymentGateway gateway;   // depends on interface, NOT concrete

    public CheckoutService(PaymentGateway gateway) {
        this.gateway = gateway;
    }

    public void completeOrder(double amount) {
        gateway.pay(amount);               // polymorphic dispatch
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Walkthrough

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\text{1. CheckoutService receives a PaymentGateway reference (abstraction).} \\
&\text{2. At runtime, the JVM dispatches gateway.pay(amount) to the actual object.} \\
&\text{3. Because CardPayment implements PaymentGateway, it satisfies the contract.} \\
&\text{4. validate() is inherited as a default; pay() is overridden as required.} \\
&\text{5. CURRENCY and currency() are accessible as PaymentGateway.CURRENCY.}
\end{aligned}
$$

## 3.3 Exhaustive Comparison Matrix — Interface vs Abstract Class

| Property | Interface | Abstract Class |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | `interface` | `abstract class` |
| Method bodies | Allowed (Java 8+ `default` / `static`) | Allowed |
| Instance variables | **Not allowed** (only constants) | Allowed (any access) |
| Constructors | **Not allowed** | Allowed |
| Inheritance form | Multiple (`implements A, B`) | Single (`extends X`) |
| Access modifiers for methods | Implicitly `public` | Any (`public`, `protected`, …) |
| `final` declaration | **Cannot** be `final` | Can be `final` |
| When to choose | **"has-a capability"** | **"is-a shared identity"** |

