### Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]
**Define an interface in Java. Can an interface contain a constructor? Justify your answer.**

**Model Answer:**
An interface in Java is a reference type that declares a contract of abstract methods (and optionally default/static methods). It is declared using the `interface` keyword.
**No**, an interface **cannot contain a constructor** because:
- Interfaces are **not instantiated**; they are purely abstract specifications.
- They cannot have instance state (only `static final` constants), so there is nothing to initialize through a constructor.
- The Java Language Specification (JLS) forbids constructors inside an `interface` body.

