## Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

### Question A — [KTU University Exam – Dec 2024]

**(a)** Explain the concept of interface specification in Java. Discuss how multiple inheritance is achieved using interfaces with a suitable example. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** What are default methods in interfaces? Explain with an example how the **diamond problem** is resolved when a class implements two interfaces having the same default method. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a)** Interface Specification & Multiple Inheritance

Interface specification in Java is the mechanism of declaring an **abstract contract** that classes must fulfil, using the `interface` keyword. It specifies **method signatures** (without committing to an implementation) and may include **constants**. A class uses the `implements` clause to honour one or more interfaces.

Multiple inheritance is achieved because **a class can implement any number of interfaces**, thereby inheriting the **type** of each. This allows a class to be polymorphic with respect to multiple, otherwise unrelated, contracts.

```java
interface Drawable { void draw(); }
interface Resizable { void resize(double factor); }

class Circle implements Drawable, Resizable {
    double radius;
    @Override public void draw()      { System.out.println("Drawing Circle"); }
    @Override public void resize(double f) { this.radius *= f; }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Circle c = new Circle();
        c.draw();
        c.resize(2.0);
        Drawable d = c;   // upcast to interface type
        d.draw();
    }
}
```

Here `Circle` inherits the *type* of both `Drawable` and `Resizable`. A `Circle` object can be referenced through any of these interface types, enabling **polymorphism across multiple abstractions**.

**(b)** Default Methods and the Diamond Problem

**Default methods** (introduced in Java 8) are interface methods declared with the `default` keyword that have a **concrete implementation**. They allow interfaces to evolve with new methods **without breaking existing implementers**.

```java
interface Engine {
    default void start() {
        System.out.println("Engine starting...");
    }
}

interface Electric {
    default void start() {
        System.out.println("Electric motor starting...");
    }
}
```

**The Diamond Problem:** A class that implements both `Engine` and `Electric` inherits **two competing `start()` methods**. Java forces explicit resolution:

```java
class HybridCar implements Engine, Electric {
    @Override
    public void start() {
        Engine.super.start();   // explicit choice — engine version
    }
}
```

If the override is omitted, the compiler raises:
> *error: class HybridCar inherits unrelated defaults for start() from types Engine and Electric.*

Resolution methods:
1. **Override the conflicting method** in the implementing class.
2. Use the qualified syntax `InterfaceName.super.methodName()` to choose a specific parent.
3. Re-declare the method as `abstract` to defer to a sub-class.

---

### Question B — [KTU University Exam – Jun 2023] — Alternative Choice

**(a)** Differentiate between an abstract class and an interface in Java. When would you prefer one over the other? **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program to define an interface `BankAccount` with methods `deposit(double)` and `withdraw(double)`. Implement this interface in two classes `SavingsAccount` and `CurrentAccount`. Demonstrate polymorphism by passing both to a common `Transaction` method. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a)** Abstract Class vs Interface — Differences

| Feature | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Inheritance | Single (`extends`) | Multiple (`implements`) |
| State | Can have instance variables | Only `public static final` constants |
| Methods | Abstract + concrete | Abstract + `default` + `static` |
| Constructors | Allowed | Not allowed |
| Access modifiers | Any | Methods implicitly `public` |
| When to choose | Shared base class with common code/state | Capability/role across unrelated classes |

**When to prefer:**
- Choose **abstract class** when there is a clear *is-a* relationship and shared code/state (e.g., `Animal` → `Dog`).
- Choose **interface** when there is a *has-a capability* or *role* (e.g., `Serializable`, `Comparable`) and unrelated classes must be treated uniformly.

**(b)** Java Program — `BankAccount` Interface

```java
interface BankAccount {
    void deposit(double amount);
    void withdraw(double amount);
    double getBalance();
}

class SavingsAccount implements BankAccount {
    private double balance = 0;
    public void deposit(double amt) {
        balance += amt;
        System.out.println("Savings deposit: " + amt);
    }
    public void withdraw(double amt) {
        if (balance >= amt) balance -= amt;
        else System.out.println("Insufficient funds");
    }
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }
}

class CurrentAccount implements BankAccount {
    private double balance = 0;
    public void deposit(double amt) {
        balance += amt;
        System.out.println("Current deposit: " + amt);
    }
    public void withdraw(double amt) {
        balance -= amt;   // overdraft allowed (simplified)
    }
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }
}

public class Transaction {
    public static void perform(BankAccount acc, double amt, boolean isDeposit) {
        if (isDeposit) acc.deposit(amt);
        else acc.withdraw(amt);
        System.out.println("Balance: " + acc.getBalance());
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount s = new SavingsAccount();
        BankAccount c = new CurrentAccount();
        perform(s, 1000, true);
        perform(c, 500, false);
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Savings deposit: 1000.0
Balance: 1000.0
Current deposit: 0.0  ← (no deposit performed)
Balance: -500.0
```

The `Transaction.perform()` method accepts **any** `BankAccount`, demonstrating **polymorphism via interface specification**.

